<![CDATA[
<p>A  <strong><em>(binary)  <strong><em>relation</em></strong> from a set <span class="math inline">\(A\)</span> to set <span class="math inline">\(B\)</span></em></strong> is a subset of the Cartesian product of <span class="math inline">\(A\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(B\)</span>. For a relation <span class="math inline">\(R \subseteq A \times B\)</span>,</p>
<ul>
<li><p>the set <span class="math inline">\(\left\{ a : (a,b) \in  
  R \right\}\)</span> is referred to as the  <strong><em>domain</em></strong> of <span class="math inline">\(R\)</span>, and</p></li>
<li><p>the set <span class="math inline">\(\left\{ b  
  : (a,b) \in R \right\}\)</span> is referred to as the  <strong><em>range</em></strong> of <span class="math inline">\(R\)</span>.</p></li>
</ul>
]]>
</field> <!-- body -->
<field name='body_src'>
<![CDATA[
A~\defn{(binary)~\defn{relation} from a set~$A$ to set~$B$} is a
subset of the Cartesian product of~$A$ and~$B$.  
For a relation~$R \subseteq A \times B$, 
\begin{itemize}
\item the set~$\cset{a : (a,b) \in
  R}$ is referred to as the~\defn{domain} of $R$, and 
\item 
the set~$\cset{b
  : (a,b) \in R}$ is referred to as the~\defn{range} of $R$.
\end{itemize}
]]>
</field> <!-- body_src -->

